Running as root
\layout Standard

If you run the filer as the `root' user then the filer will display a message
 at the top of each window to remind you.
 The root user has permission to access or change any file in the system,
 so be very careful when using the filer like this.
\layout Standard

Normally, you should log in as an ordinary user and only change to root
 when you need to.
 You can create a simple script which runs the filer as root --- something
 like this:
\layout LyX-Code

#!/bin/sh
\layout LyX-Code

su -m -c "rox $*"
\layout Standard

Then, you can get a root filer window by simply running the script and entering
 the root password.
 Remember, any file operations you perform and any programs you run from
 these windows will run as root too! Be careful!
\layout Standard

You may find that the X server won't allow root (or other users) to connect.
 Reading the manual pages for `
\family typewriter 
xauth
\family default 
' and `
\family typewriter 
xhost
\family default 
' may give you some hints, but it varies between systems (which is why this
 isn't built in to the filer!).
